dataSetInformation.common:name: Photochemical ozone formation - human health
dataSetInformation.common:generalComment: Only for Europe. Includes spatial differentiation.

impactModel.modelDescription: Considering a marginal increase in ozone formation, the LOTOS-EUROS spatially differentiated model averages over 14000 grid cells to define European factors.
impactModel.consideredMechanisms: Consideration of VOC and NOx emissions.

review.common:reviewDetails: Methods and characterization factors are well documented and accessible. Characterization models and input data not easily accessible. High environmental relevance (human health only). Comprehensive spatial differentiation at the European scale. Moderate stakeholder acceptance. Dutch government supporting the method. Potentially adaptable to generate characteriation factors for other continents if complemented by global models.

common:referenceToNameOfReviewerAndInsti.common:shortDescription: Consortium for defining the recommended Life Cycle Impact Assessment framework, methods and factors

common:referenceToCompleteReviewReport.common:shortDescription: Review report on recommended LCIA methods

common:referenceToCommissioner.common:shortDescription: Ministry of Housing, Spatial Planning and Environment (VROM)

common:commissionerAndGoal.common:project: LCIA method original development within the ReCiPe project (see www.lcia-recipe.net/). Documentation as ILCD formatted data set, mapping to the ILCD elementary flows, and additional quality checks by the ECâ€™s JRC-IES and with contractual support projects, partly financed under several Administrative Arrangements on the European Platform on LCA - EPLCA' between JRC and DG ENV, (070402/2006/443456/G4, 070307/2007/474521/G4, 070307/2008/513489/G4).
common:commissionerAndGoal.common:intendedApplications: Provide applicable spatially differentiated midpoint characterization factors for photochemical ozone formation in Europe (impacts on human health).

common:referenceToOwnershipOfDataSet.common:shortDescription: Rosalie van Zelm and Mark von Huijbregts

publicationAndOwnership.common:accessRestrictions: The data set can be used free of charge by anybody to perform LCA studies, to distribute it to third parties, to convert it to other formats, to develop own data sets etc. as long as the copyright and license conditions for the ELCD data sets and the ILCD format are met that can be accessed via http://lca.jrc.ec.europa.eu and are part of the ELCD database distribution package. Please note e.g. that reference must be given to the 'Owner of data set' (who may have additional copyright and license requirements on the particular data set that are to be met) and to the 'ELCD database' plus version number, when using the data set or parts thereof. Please note also that any modifications/omissions of the data set results in invalidity of any existing 'Official recommendation of data set by governmental body', that the impression must be avoided that this would still be an original ELCD data set, and that the content of further fields may have to be adjusted. For details see the aforementioned copyright and license conditions as well as those the 'Owner of data set' may have put into force.
